Reviewer Comments: \
\
Reviewer #1:\
Remarks to the Author:\
Taylor and Larson review the current literature on the prevalence and evolutionary importance of hybridization. I found the review to be an excellent summary of the current literature and major questions in the field. I have a few suggestions for improvement from reading the paper that I outline below:\
\
1) I wasn't sure why the authors focused on ancient hybridization as a distinct topic here, as the rest of their paper focuses more on the functional outcomes. Perhaps it is worth distinguishing between the technical and practical issues raised by studying ancient hybridization and the unanswered biological questions addressed later. In that vein I was wondering if there were other technical issues/advances that could be discussed, such as new methods for inferring selection against hybridization (e.g. Sedghifar et al. 2016 among others) and new methods for inferring ancient hybridization events when the source populations are unknown ("ghost admixture methods" like Skov et al. 2018). Later in that section the authors focus on the importance of ancient hybridization events in understanding the long-term consequences of hybridization and if that is the main emphasis I think that could be brought up earlier in the section.\
2) Another question I had was whether the authors would think it useful to add a section on the role of selection in limiting introgression or structuring the distribution of introgresison locally in the genome (sort of the inverse of the adaptive introgression section). This may be my bias but I have come to find this a very important piece of the puzzle, although it is covered in some other reviews as well. \
3) I was hoping the authors could expand on this comment in the text: "inferring adaptive introgression from genomic signatures alone should be done with caution." I think one of the main issues is that not many genomic tests are designed for admixed genomes, and thus can generate lots of false positives. Methods like ancestry frequency outliers are designed for admixed genomes but have similar limitations to e.g. Fst scans, when the number of selected sites is unknown. Furthermore, processes like heterosis can generate these signals without adaptive per se (see recent work by Bernard Kim et al. 2018). Perhaps this is a moment to appeal for the development of new methods to distinguish these processes.\
\
Minor comments:\
line 63: is hominids or hominins meant here?\
line 99: modify to recent studies?\
I thought that the conservation focus at the end of the ancient hybridization section might be better moved elsewhere (maybe a section on other implications or similar)\
line 298: I found the Lamichhaney study very interesting but wondered about the resilence of these types of barriers over long time periods (e.g. as in Schumer et al. 2017).\
line 308: Also helpful to mention experiment more by Greig et al in yeast that makes similar conclusions\
line 380: I agree that haplotype based methods will give greater insights but also require much better ancestry inference and phasing approaches than exist for most species\
line 587: Did the authors intend to highlight this line of the table?\
\
Sincerely,\
