Reviewer #3:\
Remarks to the Author:\
In this review the authors set out to discuss what insights have been and will be gained into the evolutionary importance and prevalence of hybridization in nature from the analysis of genomes. They focus, in turn, on the detection and analysis of ancient hybridization, adaptive introgression, and hybrid speciation. Most of the literature referred to relates to recent studies conducted on animals. Although there is value in reviewing this topic, I am concerned that this review is somewhat biased and incomplete in its coverage. Most notably, in the discussion of hybrid speciation, no mention at all is made of allopolyploidy. Instead, the focus is entirely on homoploid hybrid speciation, currently considered to be a rather rare form of speciation. Allopolyploidy is known to be a major mechanism of plant speciation and the analysis of genome-wide data is providing greater insights into this process from various standpoints. For example, it enables identification of the different\
parent genomes brought together and maintained in an allopolyploid species even when one or more of the parent species has/have become extinct (see Luo et al. 2017). Furthermore, it provides insights into rapid genomic changes that occur following an allopolyploid origin resulting in genome size reduction, diploidization, genome dominance etc. (see the many papers by Jonathan Wendel and others on this). Clearly, allopolyploidy is an important mechanism of hybrid speciation (a least in plants) and it is essential, therefore, to discuss it in a review that considers the significance of genome analysis to an understanding of such speciation. \
\
On the topic of homoploid hybrid speciation, the authors accept Schumer and colleagues\'92 proposals that it can only be considered proven if it is demonstrated that reproductive isolation (prezygotic and/or postzygotic) of the hybrid from its parents results directly from hybridization. This is despite the fact that others (e.g. Nieto Feliner et al. 2017, referred to in the text) have problems accepting this strict criterion. Acceptance of the criterion becomes tricky when inferring what constitutes a homoploid hybrid species. Thus, towards the end of the section on hybrid speciation the authors state, \'93Clearly, there are an increasing number of taxa for which hybridization has likely played an important role in their evolution. Some appear to be of hybrid origin, but whether they are homoploid hybrid species, or have experienced ongoing or irregular gene flow with close relatives throughout their evolutionary history remains unclear in most cases. Generally, however, there is\
insufficient data to demonstrate homoploid hybrid speciation.\'94 I am left asking what to call a hybrid known to be a sexually reproducing, self-perpetuating independent entity, which must, therefore, be reproductively isolated from its parents. Why can\'92t it be called a homoploid hybrid species? We refer to non-hybrid, sexually reproducing, self-perpetuating independent entities that are reproductively isolated from other such types as species, usually without knowing the details of how they became or currently are reproductively isolated. Why shouldn\'92t we do the same for the above hybrids. I would like the authors to help out here, rather than leaving this problem in limbo. \
\
One insight into the evolutionary importance of hybridization gained from genome wide analyses not mentioned in this review concerns the genetic structure of hybrid zones and the likelihood of introgression. Studies of hybrid zones between two poplar (Populus) species using a relatively low number of genetic markers initially indicated that hybrids were later-generation recombinants (Lexer et al. 2005, 2010; Lindtke et al. 2012) indicating introgression between the species. However, when several hundred thousands of SNPs were later employed in the analysis, it became clear that most hybrids were in fact F1s and that strong selection against post-F1 hybrids likely occurred in these hybrid zones (Lindtke et al. 2014; Christe et al. 2016) thus preventing introgression from occurring. Further studies are required to determine whether or not such greater insight from genome-wide analyses might be obtained for the genetic structure of other hybrid zones.\
\
Lastly, I would like to take issue with the general claim made at the end of paragraph 5 of the Introduction that already from genome analyses \'93..we have gained many interesting and exciting insights into the role of hybridization in adaptation and speciation.\'94 I would argue that we are only at the beginning of this and that further insights will be largely gained in the future. The results of the few analyses conducted to date involving genome-wide analysis offer promise; however, most current insights have been gained from analyses based on relatively small numbers of molecular markers. This may seem picky, but I don\'92t think one should over-egg the advances, gained so far from genome-wide analyses, except perhaps in regard to allopolyploidy!\
\
Additional minor edits, comments and suggestions are provided on the annotated WORD file of the manuscript.\
